	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu Oct 14, 2010 1:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">miker00lz wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">miker00lz wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">i will personally never develop anything using the .NET framework. same question. why would anybody develop a single system app?</div><br />Yeah, why not develop all NES games in a high-level language that can be recompiled for Sega Master System?</div><br />that's obviously entirely different than writing desktop computer software.</div>
<br />C64 and ZX Spectrum were once popular desktop computers. Infocom went to the trouble of making an interpreted virtual machine called the Z-machine, which could be considered the 1980s counterpart to modern JVM and CLR, so that its games wouldn't be tied to one 8-bit ISA. And no, the CLR implemented by .NET isn't really a single-vendor platform; see <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mono_%28software%29" class="postlink">Mono</a>.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


